<DocsLayout title="What is an AI coding agent" currentSlug="ai/agents">
  <h1>What is an AI coding agent</h1>
  <p>
    An AI coding agent is a large language model given tools -- typically a
    file system, a shell, and sometimes a browser -- and let loose on a
    task with some autonomy over how it gets there. The model reads code,
    decides what to change, makes the change, and checks the result, in a
    loop, rather than just answering a question in a chat window.
  </p>

  <h2>Agent vs. autocomplete</h2>
  <p>
    Inline autocomplete (predicting the next few lines as you type) and an
    agent (given a task, it plans, edits multiple files, runs commands,
    and iterates) are different tools for different jobs. Autocomplete
    stays in your loop; an agent runs ahead of it and reports back.
  </p>

  <h2>The read-plan-act-verify loop</h2>
  <p>
    Most agent frameworks converge on the same shape: read enough context
    to understand the task, form a plan, take an action (edit a file, run
    a command), observe the result, and repeat until the task looks done
    or it needs to ask for help. The "verify" step -- actually running
    tests or checking output, not just assuming the edit worked -- is
    what separates a useful agent from one that confidently breaks things.
  </p>

  <h2>Why credentials matter</h2>
  <p>
    An agent with shell access can do anything you could do from a
    terminal. That's the whole point, and also the reason CommandCenter
    keeps agent credentials in an encrypted store rather than plaintext
    env files -- see <a href="/docs/credentials">Credential store</a>.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
